post_text:
Our Eagleswood Elementary School 2020 yearbook will be distributed to all of our students thanks to the generosity of our Eagleswood PTA who purchased a yearbook for each student. Our sixth grade students learn how to create this project using the Adobe Creative Suite software. They complete each page from scratch. Thank you to the sixth grade graduates who worked on these pages and did a great job!

This yearbook contains all of the memories of the 2019-2020 school year and it is certainly a year we will never forget!

post_text: Fourth grade wasnâ€™t able to go on their annual field trip to Trenton, so Ms. Candurra and Ms. Lowenberg brought the trip to them! The students went on a â€œtourâ€ of different rooms in the State House, as well as explored different sights around the area and got to learn the history of the State House. Later in the day, a State House Tour Representative joined the class on a video chat and performed the Make-A-Law Program with the kids. The class was sworn in as senators and then got to debate and vote on a proposed bill!

post_text: Our 4th graders did a science experiment using three pieces of bread. One piece was touched by dirty hands, one touched by hands with hand sanitizer on them, and one touched with hands washed with soap and water. Check out the results from one of the students and note the importance of hand washing, and how hand sanitizer is not as effective as using soap and water!

National Camp-In

Looking for something to do with your kids this weekend? Whether in your backyard or in your living room, join families across the country live on Facebook for a day of fun virtual adventures!

From camp-style cooking and friendly competitions, to special guests and campfire singalongs, this virtual event will bring the best parts of Scouting to life!

This National Camp-In is free and open to all families â€“ including families whose children are not currently in Scouting.

post_text: A few months ago the West Creek postmaster asked if a class at Eagleswood would like to create Earth Day stamps for the 50th Anniversary of Earth Day to be displayed at the post office. Mrs. Randall chose second grade because they had just learned about stamps in Social Studies with Miss Schaub. They designed the stamps and sent them off to the postmaster. Postmaster Andrews chose her favorite and sent it to the main post office to be â€œcancelledâ€. On Wednesday, April 8th, a writer for Linn's Stamp News contacted Mrs. Randall to ask about the story behind the making of the stamp. So cool!! Postmaster Andrews took photos so we could send them out since it is difficult to see them in person at this time. Congratulations to our 2nd grader, Kayleigh, for her stamp design being chosen!

On Wednesday, April 8th, a writer for Linn's Stamp News contacted Mrs. Randall to ask about the story behind the making of the stamp. So cool!! Postmaster Andrews took photos so we could send them out since it is difficult to see them in person at this time. Congratulations to our 2nd grader, Kayleigh, for her stamp design being chosen!

post_text: Fourth grade had a fun math lesson planning their own Thanksgiving meal! They used their calculation skills to estimate, as well as adding their items to get their total cost. The students meals needed to include appetizers, drinks, food/side dishes and dessert. They were allotted a budget of $50.00. Everyone reached their targeted goal, some only pennies away from it! Not only were the students practicing learned skills and concepts, but life skills that they will need. A fun time was had by all! Great job 4th grade!

post_text: The 1st grade students were exploring how to make a "10" in math class. They practiced using a large 10 frame that they put on the floor. The children standing on the 10 frame wore the red pinnies. The children outside the 10 frame wore the white pinnies. The students then decided how many white pinnies needed to go on the 10 frame to make a 10. Then they added 10 plus the number of students still outside the frame. The students had great fun completing this activity!

post_text: The second grade class designed, tested, and analyzed data to determine which materials have properties best suited to their group's model boat. They worked together to try to have their boat float in a small body of water. Students competed to see which boat could hold the most pennies. They had a blast!
